Bring a large #pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut crosswise into 1⁄2-inch-thick half-moons.
Trim and slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or
grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounces} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally,
until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve 1⁄2 cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 4 servings), then drain.

While pasta cooks, rinse @shrimp{10%ounces} under cold water, then pat dry with
#paper towels{}.

Season all over with @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}
and @pepper{}.

Once pasta has cooked for ~{5%minutes}, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon}
in a large pan over medium heat. Add zucchini, scallion whites, and garlic;
cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly softened and lightly browned,
~{2-4%minutes}.

Stir in shrimp, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounces},
and 1⁄4 cup reserved pasta cooking water (1⁄2 cup for 4 servings). Bring to a boil,
then reduce to a low simmer. TIP: If pasta isn't done cooking yet, ladle pasta
water directly from pot.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until shrimp are opaque and cooked through and
zucchini is tender, ~{3-4%minutes}.

To pan with shrimp, add drained spaghetti and @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP
for 4 servings). Cook, stirring, until butter has melted and everything is
coated in sauce, ~{1-2%minutes}. TIP: If sauce seems too thick, stir in more
reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired. TIP: For extra richness,
finish pasta with a drizzle of @?olive oil{}.

Divide pasta between shallow bowls. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.